title.narrative: CHILD PROTECTION IN EMERGENCY

description.narrative: Girls and boys affected by humanitarian crises, including children affected by armed conflict, displacement and unsafe migration are assisted, reintegrated and provided appropriate support as per CCCs, which contributes to Prevention Of Harmful Practice, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: CHILD PROTECTION outcome: Girls and boys vulnerable and exposed to violence, abuse and exploitation are better protected by institutional (formal and informal) and legislative frameworks which include services and systems.

title.narrative: Girls and boys affected by humanitarian crises, including children affected by armed conflict, displacement and unsafe migrationare assisted, reintegrated and provided appropriate support as per CCCs

description.narrative: UNICEF Supported provision of specialized emergency services to 533,611 children and care givers with focus on Family Tracing and Reunification (FTR) and community based Mental Health and PSS. As of 15 August, the security and political situation in the country further evolved with the withdrawal of the foreign troops and the massive evacuation, in which context UNICEF played a major role on providing care, support, family tracing and reunification of approximately 750 vulnerable children including 230 UASC impacted by the evacuations. Despite suspension of the Monitoring and Reporting Mechanisms, UNICEF continued to monitor, report and respond to the grave violations. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:12/01/2022
